{"id":"2004.12228","submitter":"Quanmin Guo","authors":"Quanmin Guo","title":"Redefining the Phase Space for Ideal Gas Systems Resolves the Gibbs\n  Paradox","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For an ideal gas consisting N molecules within a volume V, the volume\naccessible to each molecule at an instantaneous time is V/N. The rest of the\nvolume, (N-1)(V/N), is occupied by other (N-1) molecules. The textbook\nassumption that a molecule can access any location inside the volume V at one\ninstantaneous in time is wrong leading to the Gibbs paradox. By taking into\naccount the correct physical space for individual molecules, the partition\nfunction for the N-molecule system is obtained without using any correction\nfactor which gives rise to the correct entropy of the system. There is thus no\nneed to argue about the distinguishability of molecules. Entropy of mixing two\nquantities of ideal gasses is zero no matter the gasses are the same type or\ndifferent types. With the appropriate assignment of the phase space, the\nentropy of the system has the expected property of being extensive and the\nGibbs paradox is removed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 25 Apr 2020 20:18:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-28"}
