{"id":"2004.12341","submitter":"Daniel Franco Coronil","authors":"T. Chacon Rebollo and D. Franco Coronil","title":"Predictive data assimilation through Reduced Order Modeling for\n  epidemics with data uncertainty","comments":"14 pages, 22 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.PE cs.NA math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this article, we develop a data assimilation procedure to predict the\nevolution of epidemics with data uncertainty, with application to the Covid-19\npandemic. We construct a vademecum of solutions by solving the SIR epidemic\nmodel for a set of data neighboring the estimated real (or official) ones. A\nreduced basis is constructed from this vademecum through Proper Orthogonal\nDecomposition (POD). The reduced POD base is then applied to assimilate the\npandemic data (infected, recovered, deceased) during the period in which data\nare known, by a least squares procedure. The fitted curves are then used to\npredict the evolution of the pandemic in the next days. Validation tests for\nAndalusia region (Spain), Italy and Spain show accurate predictions for 7 days\nthat improve as the number of assimilated data increases.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 26 Apr 2020 10:20:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-28"}
